<body>
<div1 type="letter" n="1900-08-14">
<head>Report from William Crawford Gorgas to the Surgeon General, August 14, 1900</head>
<pb n="1" id="f02082001"/>
<opener>
Gorgas Report to S. G. Aug 14, 1900<lb/>
Headquarters Division of Cuba.<lb/>
OFFICE OF CHIEF <hi>SANITARY OFFICER</hi> OF HAVANA<lb/>
<hi rend="italic">LA MAESTRANZA</hi><lb/>
<hi rend="italic">CALLE DE CUBA</hi><lb/>
<hi rend="italic">ENTRE <hi>CUARTELES <unclear>Y</unclear></hi> CHACON</hi>.<lb/>
<dateline>
Havana, Cuba <date value="1900-08-14">August 14th, 1900</date>
</dateline><lb/>
To the<lb/>
Surgeon General, U.S.A.,<lb/>
Washington, D.C.<lb/>
<salute>Dear General:-</salute>
</opener>
<p>I desire to call your attention to certain points<lb/>
in the report for the month of July. You will see that the total<lb/>
number of deaths for the month is 518. The deaths for July for the<lb/>
past ten years have been as follows:</p>
<p>
<table rows="5" cols="4">
<row>
<cell>1890</cell><cell>891</cell><cell>1895</cell><cell>685</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>1891</cell><cell>738</cell><cell>1896</cell><cell>1098</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>1892</cell><cell>577</cell><cell>1897</cell><cell>1269</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>1893</cell><cell>701</cell><cell>1898</cell><cell>1532</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>1894</cell><cell>736</cell><cell>1899</cell><cell>680</cell>
</row>
</table>
</p>
<p>This month is considerably lower than the lowest,<lb/>
that of 1892, and is very much lower than that of the same month of<lb/>
last year.</p>
<p>We had thirty deaths from yellow fever this month; a con-<lb/>
siderably larger number than we had for the same month of last<lb/>
year,; but below the average for normal years. Taking the years from<lb/>
1885 to 1895, I take these as normal years, not being effected by<lb/>
war or any other unusual circumstance, and it gives us an average fo<lb/>
July of 34 deaths from yellow fever. The greatest item in yellow<lb/>
fever is, I think, the number of non-immunes present; and this, in<lb/>
Havana, is effected principally by the Spanish immigration. The<lb/>
following is the number of immigrants per year from 1885vto 1889:</p>
<p>
<table rows="5" cols="2">
<row>
<cell>1885</cell><cell>5498</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>1886</cell><cell>9195</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>1887</cell><cell>8593</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>1888</cell><cell>8980</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>1889</cell><cell>8707</cell>
</row>
</table>
</p>
<pb n="2" id="f02082002"/>
<p>Headquarters Division of Cuba.<lb/>
OFFICE OF CHIEF <hi>SANITARY OFFICER</hi> OF HAVANA<lb/>
LA MAESTRANZA<lb/>
CALLE DE CUBA<lb/>
ENTRE <hi>CUARTELES</hi> <unclear>Y</unclear> CHACON<lb/>
<hi rend="italic">Havana, Cuba</hi><lb/>
<hi rend="italic">1900</hi></p>
<p>-2-</p>
<p>This is an average ofaabout 8000 per year. From July, 1899<lb/>
to July 1900, there was 25,000 immigrants, three times as many as<lb/>
the average for the above years. Thus it appears, that although<lb/>
at present we have three times the normal non-immune population for<lb/>
July, we have less than one-third the normal death rate for that<lb/>
month from yellow fever. From these figures we can deduce the fact<lb/>
that the normal death rate for non-immunes for July from yellow<lb/>
fever is 4.2 persons per 1000, which carried out for a year would<lb/>
give 50 deaths per 1000. We had this year a death rate for July<lb/>
from yellow fever of 1.2 persons per 1000, which would give us a<lb/>
death rate of 14 per 1000 for a year.</p>
<p>I think that these figures will show that the general<lb/>
sanitary condition of Havana is better than it has been at any time<lb/>
within the past ten years, and that the number of yellow fever cases<lb/>
is greatly below what we could ordinarly expect. The general mortal-<lb/>
ity is the best measure of the sanitary condition, and infectious<lb/>
diseases like yellow fever are effected largely by other circum-<lb/>
stances; in this case almost entirely by the number of non-immunes<lb/>
present.</p>
<closer>
<salute>Very respectfully,</salute>
<signed>W.C. Gorgas.</signed>
Major and Surgeon U.S.A.,<lb/>
Chief Sanitary Officer.<lb/>
3177<lb/>
</closer>
</div1>
